<TEXT>
oregon voters face a measure tuesday 
that urges congress to let the state halt shipments of raw logs 
overseas when domestic lumber mills are starving for timber and 
workers jobs are jeopardized 
the ballot proposal called measure 2 seeks to ban export of 
logs cut on state land and calls on congress to make permanent a ban 
of export of logs cut on federal land 
both supporters and opponents view measure 2 as a symbolic test 
of the public will with jobs at mills jeopardized by both the high 
prices for raw logs and by environmentalist lawsuits aimed at 
protecting the rare northern spotted owl and the ancient forests 
where they live 
this is the first opportunity anybody in the united states has 
had to say we want timber jobs we need timber jobs thats really 
the issue on tuesday said doug stout vice president for lands 
and timber for bohemia inc a lumber company in eugene that has 
contributed 100000 in support of measure 2 
but because of a us supreme court ruling on the same issue five 
years ago the options of oregon voters are strictly limited the 
high court ruled that only congress has the right to restrict trade 
declaring an oregon law banning log exports unconstitutional 
because of the ruling congress would have to pass enabling 
legislation for the state export ban to become effective even if it 
is passed tuesday as most expect it will 
the bush administration is seeking just the opposite having 
proposed to lift a ban of exports of logs cut on federal land 
currently in effect on a yeartoyear basis to take advantage of 
premium prices paid by log buyers in china japan and korea 
within the timber industry itself opinions are mixed many 
companies make money exporting unprocessed logs while others are 
struggling obtain logs for their mills 
the pacific rim trade association which opposes export 
restrictions has decided to concentrate its efforts on defeating 
the enabling legislation in congress rather than seeking victory in 
tuesdays referendum said association executive director rolf 
glerum 
we didnt feel we could raise the money to fight measure 2 
said glerum even if we were to win it it still wouldnt have any 
effect the whole thing is triggered by the congress 
the groups members include weyerhaeuser co the leading 
exporter of raw logs in the northwest as well as stevedoring 
companies shippers and the international longshoremens and 
warehousemens union 
one reason we oppose this is we feel it is the camels nose 
under the tent said glerum because supporters would just as 
soon see all log exports banned 
indeed a recent white paper from the oregon natural resources 
council pointed to stopping all log exports as a quick fix to the 
timber supply crunch that has plagued northwest mills the past year 
glerum and other opponents expect measure 2 to pass a recent 
poll by the oregonian newspaper showed support running more than 
8to1 
a campaign spending report from may 26 showed citizens to save 
oregon jobs raised nearly 800000 to push for passage primarily 
from nonexporting timber companies 
were talking primarily about oregon logs for oregon jobs 
said pat amedeo a lobbyist who serves on the steering committee for 
the campaign the big battle because it is a nontraditional 
election date is to get enough voters to the polls 
i think in terms of sending a message back to washington dc 
which is part of what the ballot measure does the more people who 
vote the more significant the message 
state rep bernie agrons was one of the few voices in the 
legislature opposing the measure 
a former vice president of weyerhaeuser agrons said the measure 
would deprive the common school fund and counties of revenues from 
state timber 
last year 125 million in state timber revenues went to the 
common school fund and 183 million went to local governments 
predominantly schools export logs are generally considered to bring 
a premium price about 25 percent higher than domestic logs 
</TEXT>
