<TEXT>
its an unwritten law of american business you 
cant sell computer software on the honor system and expect to be a 
success 
unless youre bob wallace president owner and exchief 
programmer of seattlebased quicksoft publisher of pcwrite the 
acclaimed shareware wordprocessor for personal computers then 
you break the unwritten law 
i encourage people to copy the software and then encourage them 
to pay for it after using it its like public television the 
40yearold wallace said last week 
users who pay and register get extra benefits the printed 
manual telephone support quicksofts newsletter and updates of the 
program 
but then there are intangible benefits youre doing the right 
thing youre helping us out keeping us in business he said and 
that leads to newer and better versions of pcwrite 
i dont worry about the people who dont register i worry 
about the people who do register he said i want to make sure 
theyre happy 
if theyre happy and were making a reasonable profit thats 
good 
its good enough for quicksoft with about 30 employees to 
expand its product base too on tuesday the company announced its 
new filesearch and hypertext informationlinking utility 
scheduled for latesummer shipping 
quicksoft also has published its first catalog of thirdparty 
software it selects and supports for use with pcwrite 
wallace whose catchphrase is making a living not a 
killing chose his profession at age 11 i read a readers 
digest article the man who talked to machines he said i was 
one of the people that just knew then i would be a programmer 
he found computers to work on with an explorer scout troop 
sponsored by control data corp in bethesda md then at the 
university of maryland brown university and the university of 
washington 
i got kind of discouraged because computers were so expensive 
i couldnt own one and i really wanted to own one so i kind of got 
distracted and went off i was living on an island in puget sound 
for a while he said 
the first personal computers appeared about the time he founded 
the northwest computer club in 1976 he went to work for the retail 
computer store in seattle 
in 1978 he was the 10th employee hired by microsoft corp the 
software company that created the ibmstandard personal computer 
operating systems 
sometime in 82 i found myself thinking gee microsoft is 
getting huge and im kind of getting lost here he said 
microsoft had 300 employees then it now has about 3800 worldwide 
he started writing a program for word processing 
i thought i could do something people would really like and 
really felt right but i didnt know if i could explain that i 
couldnt really run an ad saying buy my word processor it feels 
good 
he could however share his word processor using the electronic 
bulletin boards of computer hobbyists that eliminated distribution 
and advertising expenses 
the first version 10 was introduced in august 1983 with 150 
copies sent to the press and 150 to bulletin boards a pc magazine 
reviewer suggested changes wallace made them by february 1984 
wallace had written version 13 and the reviewer liked it 
that review pretty much started us out it generated enough 
interest and revenue so that i could hire our first employee uh 
who i later married 
megan dana wallace an artist draws quicksofts trademark 
office cat on the companys literature 
pcwrite typically is rated as good as or better than other 
fullfeatured word processors costing five times more than its 89 
registration fee 
its anybodys guess how many copies of pcwrite are out there 
wallace says the best estimates come from magazine surveys which 
typically estimate that 6 percent of their readers use pcwrite 
i discount that down to maybe 4 percent and thats somewhere 
between half a million and 1 million users and thats real 
exciting he said 
working from the other end we know we have paid users of about 
125000 of which 45000 are full registered users and the other 
80000 are on group licenses corporations and universities he 
said 
he expects revenues this year to be between 2 million and 3 
million sales declined to 17 million last year from 2 million in 
1987 he blames the slump on himself for putting off the decision 
to step down as chief programmer to take up exclusively the 
presidency of quicksoft 
a final thought from bob wallace 
our business is based on people being honest and people are 
thats why were successful 
