the supreme court today agreed to set 
guidelines on when employers may withdraw recognition of a labor 
union after hiring new workers to break a strike 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal of a 
ruling favoring an employer in a case stemming from a 1979 strike 
against a texas laboratory supplies company 
curtin matheson scientific inc was struck in 1979 by workers at 
its warehouse in houston after a union contract expired and the 
company locked out all 27 teamsters union members employed there 
five of the 27 employees crossed the picket line when the strike 
began june 13 1979 the company 12 days later hired 29 new 
employees to replace the remaining 22 strikers 
when the union later offered to end the strike under terms 
previously offered by management the company withdrew the offer 
along with its recognition of the union as the workers bargaining 
agent 
the national labor relations board in 1987 said the company 
illegally withdrew its recognition of the union the board said the 
company acted without adequate reason to believe the union lacked 
support from a majority of the workers then at the plant 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals overruled the board last 
november 
the company was justified in doubting that the striker 
replacements supported the union the appeals court said 
bush administration lawyers said the labor board properly refused 
to accept the companys presumption that the union had lost the 
support of the majority of workers 
strikebreakers may choose to work for financial reasons or they 
may disapprove of a strike while still supporting the union justice 
department lawyers told the court 
the case is nlrb vs curtin matheson 881685 
