<TEXT>
the supreme court today ordered a lower court 
to restudy a dispute over drug and alcohol testing for employees of 
a mass transit agency in the philadelphia area 
the justices said the lower court should reexamine its ruling in 
light of recent decisions that allowed the conrail railroad to adopt 
drug tests for its workers without first bargaining with its unions 
and allowed mandatory drug testing of railroad employees involved in 
accidents 
in the case acted on today a lower court ruling was challenged 
by both the workers and their employer the southeastern 
pennsylvania transportation authority known as septa 
septa and its workers are unhappy with different aspects of a 
ruling last december by the 3rd us circuit court of appeals 
the appeals court said septa did not violate the privacy rights 
of employees in safety sensitive jobs by requiring them to 
undergo random drug and alcohol tests 
but the appeals court based on narrower grounds barred the 
agency from testing any employees covered by the federal railway 
labor act 
the federal law bars railroads from unilaterally adopting any 
such major change in working conditions the appeals court said it 
said the unions that challenged the tests are entitled to mediation 
and conciliation procedures spelled out by the law 
the supreme court ruled on june 19 that conrail may use 
previously approved physical fitness tests to screen for drug use 
it said the addition of drug screening is a minor change not 
warranting collective bargaining 
conrails tests are not random they are to be administered 
periodically to all workers during routine physical examinations in 
addition employees returning to work after an absence would have to 
undergo the tests 
the high court last march 21 issued two key rulings on drug and 
alcohol testing in the workplace the justices upheld blood and 
urine tests for railroad workers involved in accidents and upheld 
urine tests for us customs service employees seeking 
drugenforcement jobs 
in the case acted on today septa announced in 1987 its plan to 
require random urine and breathalyzer tests for thousands of workers 
with jobs affecting the safety of its more than a million daily bus 
train streetcar and subway riders 
the agency also adopted tests for employees returning to work 
after absences those tests were declared unconstitutional by the 
3rd circuit court and septa and its unions subsequently reached a 
settlement on the returntowork tests 
the cases are septa vs transport workers union 881486 and 
united transportation union vs septa 881653 
