the supreme court refused today to allow 
resident aliens sue in federal court to collect retroactive 
unemployment benefits from the state of colorado 
the action comes 11 days after the justices ruled that congress 
has the power to strip state governments of their constitutional 
immunity against private lawsuits 
at issue in the colorado case was whether such state immunity 
should be overcome lower courts said no 
a policy of the colorado department of labors division of 
employment and training of refusing to pay unemployment benefits to 
some previously employed aliens lawfully living in the state sparked 
a 1984 lawsuit 
the suit sought to have the policy declared a violation of the 
federal unemployment tax act and to collect benefits it alleged were 
wrongfully withheld 
a federal trial judge ruled that the aliens would have to pursue 
their claims through state administrative proceedings the aliens 
appealed but the 10th us circuit court of appeals dismissed the 
suit nov 29 
noting that state court rulings and changes in immigration law 
made clear that the aliens were eligible for unemployment benefits 
the appeals court rendered moot the need for future relief 
regarding the claims for back benefits the 10th circuit court 
said the 11th amendment prohibits such a raid on the state treasury 
in federal court 
the amendment says the judicial power of the united states 
should not be construed to extend to any suit against a state 
by citizens of another state or by citizens or subjects of any 
foreign state 
in decisions dating back to 1890 the supreme court has barred 
anyone instate or out from suing an unconsenting state or state 
officials if the real target is a states treasury but in recent 
years the court has allowed some federal court lawsuits against 
states 
in the case today lawyers for the aliens said the 10th circuit 
courts bar on federal suits to recover back unemployment benefits 
was in conflict with rulings by other federal appeals courts 
the case is esparza vs valdez 881432 
