the supreme court today rejected an appeal by 
an illinois doctor ordered to pay 254000 in lawyers fees to those 
who successfully challenged a state abortion law 
the court consistent with a ruling by the justices last week in 
an airline industry bias cae let stand a lower court ruling 
stemming from a 1979 lawsuit challenging an illinois 
abortionregulating law that included criminal penalties for 
physicians who violated it 
a group of doctors sued various state officials saying the law 
violated physicians rights and those of their patients 
a federal judge barred enforcement of the law soon thereafter 
dr eugene diamond and two others asked to intervene in the case as 
defenders of the law 
diamond said he was acting to defend his patients interests and 
his own professional interests 
diamond and another doctor who has since died appealed to the 
supreme court in 1985 to overrule lower court decisions and 
reinstate the law state officials dropped out of the case 
declining to pursue it to the nations high court 
the justices in 1986 ruled that diamond lacked legal standing to 
appeal thus leaving intact the victory won by the laws challengers 
a federal judge and the 7th us circuit court of appeals 
subsequently ordered diamond to help reimburse the winners legal 
fees his share of the attorneys fees with interest is 254000 
the 7th circuit court ruled last may that diamond can be forced 
to help pay the fees even though he did not violate the 
constitutional rights of those who challenged the law only public 
officials and their agents may commit constitutional violations 
the public officials in the case were sued under a key civil 
rights law that authorizes reimbursement of attorneys fees to 
encourage legal representation for those whose rights are violated 
diamond and the others who intervened in the case in defense of 
the law for all practical purposes became the alter ego of 
the state officials the appeals court said 
we cannot ignore the fact that the intervenors unilateral 
decision to join with the state defendants in adamantly 
defending the constitutionality of the abortion act rendered them 
fullfledged parties to the lawsuit the appeals court said 
it added that the intervenors were thoroughly beaten in 
numerous court proceedings by the laws challengers 
the appeals court also rejected diamonds arguments that forcing 
him to help pay the other sides legal fees chills his freespeech 
rights 
a fee reimbursement system is not unlawful simply because it 
forces those who choose voluntarily to interject themselves into 
such lawsuits to think twice before engaging in battle the 
appeals court said 
the case is diamond vs charles 88664 
