nobody loves family reunions more than jazz 
people and what more joyous reunion could there be than that of 
singer joe williams and the count basie orchestra 
williams became a star when he joined the basie band in the 
mid1950s williams 1955 recording with the band of every day i 
have the blues made him internationally known eventually in 
1961 he struck out on his own and has had continued success 
his 70th birthday seemed like a natural occasion for a 
reunion with the basie bunch led these days by saxophonist 
frank foster it also made for a splendid opening night friday of 
the jvc jazz festival which first came to town 18 years ago as the 
newport jazz festival it has changed sponsors and names a few 
times but its still a premiere jazz bash jvc is the japanese 
victor co an electronics firm 
the carnegie hall concert showed why joe williams has endured 
his voice ranges from a whisper to a shout as comfortable with 
gospel and ballad standards as with the lowdown blues 
the first half of the concert williams and his trio led by 
pianist norman simmons explored the singers range ballads 
alternated with some shouters favorites embraceable you for 
