<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange and other 
futures markets should do a better job of cracking down on 
highpressure telephone sales tactics at member firms the staff of 
the commodity futures trading commission said monday 
the staff report praised the exchange for responding to earlier 
suggestions for improvement but said more needs to be done to 
ensure that investigative procedures adequately address the issue 
of detecting abusive oral sales representations 
one of the biggest complaints of securities and futures customers 
after the october 1987 stock market crash was that they had been 
talked into making unsuitably speculative investments without being 
properly warned of the risks 
the staff of the commission which regulates futures markets 
praised the merc for starting a program of interviewing customers to 
make sure futures brokers dont use sale pitches designed to 
override risk disclosure documents provided to customers however 
it said the exchange should routinely conduct the interviews in a 
more systematic and timely fashion 
specifically the commission staff said the merc did a poor job 
of investigating a particular firm which it did not identify that 
had attracted an unusual number of customer complaints 
the cftc division of trading and markets believes that the 
exchanges investigation was not concluded in a timely manner 
and should have included certain additional procedures such as an 
attempt to uncover high pressure sales tactics the agencys 
report said 
it also said that the exchanges requirement that most actions by 
staff investigators be authorized by an internal committee may 
unnecessarily prolong an investigation 
andrew a yemma a spokesman for the exchange said the merc 
disagreed with the commissions assessment of that particular 
investigation 
we believe our efforts were timely and thorough and we will 
attempt to bridge this gap with the cftc he said 
however he said the exchange intends to adopt a commission 
suggestion that it work more closely with the national futures 
association and will adopt an invesigatory technique used by the 
association the association sometimes has its investigators pose as 
customers as a way of uncovering sales abuses 
in another recommendation the commission said the mercs member 
firms should do a better job of supervising sales personnel who were 
hired away from other firms that got into trouble with regulators 
members of the mercantile and of other exchanges as well have 
employed and in some cases even recruited employees of firms 
subject to commission enforcement proceedings or disciplinary 
actions for sales violations the report said 
yemma said the mercantile would adopt the recommended procedures 
for monitoring such employees 
in general he said the merc believes the commission report was 
favorable for instance it praises the exchange for more than 
doubling its audit staff from 16 in may 1985 to 35 in january 1988 
futures markets regulation has become a particular focus of 
congress since the disclosure in february that the fbi had conducted 
a twoyear undercover investigation of alleged abuses members of 
congress are questioning whether futures exchanges selfregulation 
system is working and whether the commission is providing effective 
oversight of the system 
the legislative scrutiny will likely come to a head this fall 
because congress must reauthorize the commission before sept 30 or 
the agency will go out of business 
