a federal agency violated its own policy when 
it cleared the way for an ohio coal company to strip mine coal in 
the wayne national forest congressional investigators have 
concluded 
it is improper for the office of surface mining to have based 
this decision on considerations other than its stated policy said 
a report by the house interior committees mining subcommittee 
delivered to the interior department parent of the office of 
surface mining on friday and made available on monday 
agency records showed the decision to let belville coal co of 
ironton ohio to mine was based on flimsy reasoning a skimpy review 
and no independent documentation according to the report 
carl close the director of the pittsburgh office of the office 
of surface mining has said he consulted a staff attorney and 
believed he was on firm legal ground when he made the nowcontested 
decision 
close in december reversed a 1986 decision and determined that 
the company had a valid existing right to mine in the 190000acre 
forest on the ohio river in other words mineral rights that 
predated creation of the forest that the federal government was 
bound to recognize 
it is inappropriate for a decision of this magnitude involving 
approximately 5440 acres of national forest land to have been 
based on a dearth of written independent agency analysis and 
supporting agency documentation the report said 
no record exists which suggests that the office of surface 
mining conducted a thorough analysis before ruling that the 
company had a legal right to strip mine for coal said the report 
the company has submitted an application for state mining permits 
covering 180 acres spokesman todd ambs said the ohio department of 
natural resources will probably act on it sometime before the end 
of the summer 
