<TEXT>
dont expect to read about fairport convention in 
the rolling stone illustrated history of rock amp roll theyre 
not even mentioned 
and dont look for fairport convention in the billboard book of 
top 40 hits they never had a hit single 
while reunions of the rolling stones and the who make headlines 
fairport convention quietly tours the country by trailer appearing 
in small clubs 
but since four soon to be six young english musicians formed 
the band in 1967 fairport convention has produced some of the 
finest folkrock of the past two decades 
if youre asking whether i thought the band would still be 
traveling about in the late 1980s the answer would be no said 
guitarist simon nicol an original member who helped put fairport 
convention back together in 1985 
their early records were heavily influenced by the beatles and 
the byrds with spirited harmonies and a tight rhythm section 
besides nicol the group featured the brilliant guitar playing and 
songwriting of richard thompson and the songwriting and soulful 
vocals of sandy denny 
you had a band at the end of every street and for most people 
it was a phase they went through nicol recalled the unlucky 
ones got caught on the treadmill we wanted to get off the 
treadmill 
by their fourth album 1969s liege and lief fairport 
convention was recording traditional english songs and making 
greater use of the mandolin and fiddle instruments that had been 
rarely used in a rock n roll format 
they built a small but devoted following with the originals 
come all ye and meet on the ledge the traditional matty 
groves and covers of bob dylans ill keep it with mine and 
percys song 
i think that the byrds had taken their roots and made it viable 
encouraged us nicol said of the american folkrock group 
the group went through several personnel changes and by the early 
70s thompson and denny had left to pursue solo careers the band 
struggled without them eventually calling it quits in 1979 
but in august 1980 fairport convention minus denny who died 
in 1978 reunited for a concert in cropredy england encouraged by 
the response the band played again the following summer and now 
headlines an annual twoday festival of folkrock and traditional 
music 
they began recording again in 1985 with nicol and two other 
fairport convention veterans bassist dave pegg and drummer dave 
mattacks forming the core of the group thompson was well 
established as a solo star so guitarist martin allcock and fiddler 
ric sanders were recruited 
the three of us had gotten on terribly well nicol said 
wed known martin for years he was very enthusiastic and really 
wanted to play with us ric was also a fan we rehearsed three days 
and found out it was going to work 
they have since released four albums gladys leap 
expletive delighted in real time and most recently red 
and gold fairport convention has also toured extensively using 
mostly new material as well as matty groves and meet on the 
ledge 
its impossible to say what a typical fairport audience is 
because they all look different pegg said we get 17 and 
18yearold kids who have discovered the music for the first time 
and people in their 50s a lot of our audience are more familiar 
with the new stuff 
the title track from red and gold was written by ralph 
mctell a friend of the band who learned that cropredy had been the 
site in 1644 of a bloody battle during the english civil war 
the album also includes a cover of open the door richard a 
pair of instrumentals written by sanders the rose hip and the 
battle and a traditional ballad the beggars song 
its just surprising when you come up with traditional songs 
that people havent heard before pegg said the best ones have 
been recorded if not by us then by other bands like steeleye span 
they got about 50 percent of the really good songs and we got the 
rest 
