john amos has worked as an advertising 
copywriter a standup comic a variety show writerperformer and 
even as a regular on mary tyler moores popular television sitcom in 
which he played gordy the weatherman 
but in his more than 20 years in and out of show business the 
broad powerfully built actor never appeared in a shakespearean 
play that changed recently with his portrayal of sir toby belch in 
twelfth night the opening production of the new york 
shakespeare festivals annual summer sojourn in central park 
and amos has found himself in a highpowered company of movie and 
theater names that includes jeff goldblum michelle pfeiffer mary 
elizabeth mastrantonio gregory hines stephen collins and fisher 
stevens 
the actor tried out for the role at the urging of james earl 
jones a veteran of the shakespearean repertory and one of the best 
othellos of recent years 
they were sitting in a trailer last year while working on the 
eddie murphy movie coming to america when jones told him if 
you dont try shakespeare it will just loom as a bigger and more 
insurmountable obstacle to you so you just might as well go ahead 
and take your best shot treat it as you would another play 
i had auditioned him before for another play and didnt give 
him the role recalls joseph papp head of the new york 
shakespeare festival but i thought gee hes an interesting 
actor with an imposing figure and good clear speech i told him 
you should look at shakespeares plays because there are many roles 
you could play 
after reading parts of twelfth night for papp and director 
harold guskin amos got the role of funloving highspirited sir 
toby 
my biggest concern was that i didnt develop an affected 
accent amos recounts 
amos born in newark nj didnt start out to be an actor his 
big dream was to play football but nothing came of it 
his acting career didnt get going until he moved to california 
my entree into show business came because of my writing during 
the day i was working for an advertising agency in los angeles at 
night i was moonlighting on a local television variety show called 
lohman and barkley as a writerperformer wed do 90 minutes of 
contemporary comedy and satirical bits 
out of that job came a position as a staff writer on the leslie 
uggams show a shortlived variety show on cbs in 1969 on it 
amos helped write what he calls a forerunner of todays situation 
comedies about middleclass blacks it was a 15minute segment 
called sugar hill in which miss uggams played the wife lincoln 
kilpatrick her husband and johnny brown her brother 
sugar hill taught me a great deal about the structure of 
situation comedy he says now so that later when i got 
involved in performing in a situation comedy i felt i had a slight 
edge on some of the other actors 
his job on the leslie uggams show won amos a role the 
following year on a new comedy series starring mary tyler moore his 
role of gordy the weatherman was his first national recognition 
amos had studied acting at a small theater in los angeles but he 
likes to think he honed his acting skills working as a standup 
comic in clubs in new yorks greenwich village in the late 60s 
i wasnt very good he says now but its the best training 
any actor can get particularly if you use your own material then 
you can gauge whether or not your perception of whats funny is 
funny to the general public 
amos lived in california for about 15 years before coming back to 
new york he was able to support himself by occasional television 
series like the tim conway comedy hour and future cop as 
well as commercials but he returned to the east coast and new 
jersey seven years ago to do more theater 
i had started to loose my hustle he says im not the kind 
of guy who can just lie by the pool waiting for my agent to call 
last year amos became artistic director and artistinresidence 
for a theater located in the grant avenue community center in 
plainfield nj after its mayor richard taylor asked him to do a 
few fundraisers 
he also staged the theaters first offering forever my 
darling a play by dan owens it takes place in the 1950s and 
concerns four black women who want to become the first female rhythm 
and blues singing group amos has even optioned the movie rights 
work on commercial projects like the upcoming sylvester stallone 
movie lockup gives amos the financial freedom to spend more 
with his fledgling theater 
i think im pretty much living the ideal life staying here in 
the east so i can be close to my theater doing i hope one 
picture a year and as much stage work as possible he says 
thats the best of both worlds 
