<TEXT>
when next years head count is done census 
bureau officials expect to report there are more people aged 65 and 
over than there were americans at the time of the civil war 
the 1860 census found 314 million americans the 1990 count is 
expected to find 316 million people 65 and older 132 million of 
those being 75 and older the 1830 census counted 129 million 
people 
there is no historical precedent for the aging of our 
population we are in the midst of a new social phenomenon wrote 
beth j soldo and emily m agree in americas elderly a study 
for the private population reference bureau we cannot foresee all 
the repercussions implications or social changes stemming from the 
presence of so many older persons and the aging of society 
people born in 1900 could expect to live 47 years life 
expectancy passed 50 in 1908 topped 60 in the 1930s and hit 70 in 
the 60s americans born today can expect to live about 75 years 
thanks largely to better medical care 
the elderly comprise about 122 percent of the population well 
over half are women 70 percent say theyre healthy and 
threefourths own their homes they also spend a greater percentage 
of what are often fixed incomes on food housing and health care 
than younger people 
but take a closer look 
by definition the elderly are 65 and up but the mix is changing 
in 1960 61 percent of the population was 65 to 74 and 31 percent 
was 75 and older by 1987 72 percent were 65 to 74 and 5 percent 
were 75 or older 
a halfcentury ago men and women comprised equal numbers of the 
elderly but women began living longer in the 1930s as pregnancyand 
childbirthrelated deaths began declining women now live an average 
783 years compared with 715 years for men and comprise 592 
percent of those age 65 and over 
as of 1988 103 percent of all american males were 65 or older 
compared with 143 percent of all women 
the problems of old age in america are largely the problems of 
women six out of every 10 older americans are women said dr 
robert butler a former director of the national institute on aging 
in general older women have fewer financial assets and 
because they typically outlive their spouses are more dependent on 
adult children and formal health care services agree and soldo 
wrote 
and that poses a problem with the need for home care for many 
elderly rising just as social change threatens to undermine the 
traditional source of that care says researcher alice t day in a 
1985 population reference bureau report she estimated 66 million 
elderly people needed longterm care but only 14 million were in 
nursing homes the rest were helped by families but small families 
mean fewer young people to care for the elderly and most of them 
face other obligations including jobs 
while elderly women tend to be widows 80 percent of men aged 65 
to 74 are married as are 66 percent of those aged 75 and over 
as people age health is of increasing concern four out of 
every five noninstitutionalized older persons have at least one 
chronic condition and many have more than one said soldo and 
agree the most common of these diseases are arthritis 
hypertension heart disease and hearing impairments 
the national center for health statistics reported in 1984 that 
23 percent of the elderly had trouble completing at least one common 
task like shopping preparing meals and housework 
nevertheless a survey by the center found that 70 percent of 
elderly considered themselves to be in good or excellent health 
those with higher incomes were more likely to list themselves in 
excellent health 
since most elderly people are retired they have lower average 
incomes in 1986 median income for families headed by someone 65 
and older was 19932 about 62 percent of that for families headed 
by someone 25 to 64 the senate special committee on aging in 1985 
reported a median income of 20354 for families with a 65 to 
74yearold head 16412 for those headed by 75 to 84yearolds 
and 15111 for 85 and over 
with less cash the elderly tend to spend a bigger percentage of 
it on food housing and health care than do younger people even so 
business now views the elderly as a market segment of growing 
importance and has begun targeting products and advertising 
another place where the elderly have attracted attention is the 
voting booth more than one in five voters in the 1986 congressional 
elections was 65 and over while 46 percent of all eligible voters 
went to the polls 651 percent of those 65 to 74 voted the most of 
any population segment 
the senate committee found that most older people are adequately 
housed although some have problems finding affordable homes in 
1985 threefourths of elder households owned their home and 25 
percent rented males were more likely to own than were females and 
those over age 75 were more likely to rent 
the elderly tended to occupy older homes 36 percent living in 
house built before 1940 compared to 21 percent of younger people 
the 1983 annual housing survey found 10 percent of the homes 
occupied by the elderly with some serious flaw in such areas as 
plumbing electrical structure and heating 
