<TEXT>
here is a look at action in state legislatures on 
issues affecting the elderly 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
arizona will borrow more than 51 million this 
year from state employee retirement funds and tax some pension 
benefits as part of a plan to eliminate a 150 million shortage in a 
32 billion budget 
gov rose mofford opposed using retirement funds but is expect to 
sign the budgetbalancing package unions and retirees also opposed 
it 
arizona will reduce its pension contribution for one year then 
repay the funds in future years another 22 million would be 
raised by taxing any pension benefits over 2500 for local state 
and federal retirees 
local and state pensions are not now taxed and federal retirees 
are taxed on anything over 2500 the change was made in part to 
comply with the us supreme courts ruling that all government 
retirees be taxed equally 
lawmakers also halved a school tax for residents of retirement 
communities that do not have organized school districts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
gov joe frank harris is considering a special 
legislative session to revise the state tax on federal pensions to 
comply with the supreme court ruling the tax draws an 50 million 
to 70 million annually 
harris assigned experts to study the issue and advise him on 
whether to eliminate the tax on federal pension benefits or start 
taxing those of state and local employees he hasnt said what 
approach he favors 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the legislature this year doubled the staff of 
the ombudsman responsible for 6000 residents of 38 nursing homes 
and 617 adultcare homes it authorized money for her to hire an 
assistant 
next year lawmakers will be asked to tackle a tougher issue 
said sandy sandy rongitsch the longtermcare ombudsman there 
currently is nothing in the states laws regulating unlicensed care 
homes 
lawmakers also will be asked to expand the ombudsmans staff so 
the elderly on neighbor islands can be given more immediate service 
rongitsch said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
legislation before the general assembly 
could affect elderly people who drive a car fill out a state tax 
return or face the possibility of physical or financial exploitation 
one measure which cleared the senate and is pending in the 
house would require annual road tests for drivers 87 and older 
those 8186 would be tested every two years the current requirement 
for testing every four years for those over 69 would be kept for 
those aged 7580 but dropped for those 74 and under 
a pending measure would allow 15year prison terms for those who 
coerce or deceive elderly people into giving up their money others 
would allow hearsay evidence of abuse to be considered by a judge to 
help determine if a person over 60 was abused and would require a 
judge to consider a victims age and health when ruling on a motion 
for a continuance in a trial of elder abuse 
also before the general assembly is legislation to restore an 
extra 1000 state tax exemption for the elderly that was 
effectively erased last year by federal tax law revisions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the top legislative priority for elderly 
kansans is expansion of the 1989 kansas senior care act which 
provides 250000 this year for inhome services to keep people out 
of nursing homes as long as possible 
the act passed this year is a modest program that should be 
broadened said lyndon drew director of planning for the department 
of aging inhome services will be a top priority under the 
act the state will develop three pilot projects for homemaker and 
personal care services to be expanded statewide in four years 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a new law protects the elderly from 
insurance companies selling useless policies and pending 
legislation is designed to protect them from exorbitant physician 
fees 
the new law prohibits sale of medicare supplemental insurance to 
anyone not covered by medicare 
pending before a house committee is a plan to bar unreasonable 
fees by doctors serving medicare patients doctors now can submit a 
bill to medicare and accept payment based on what medicare lists as 
reasonable fees or bill the patient who then files for reimbursment 
and would have to pay the difference the pending measure would 
require doctors to go through medicare 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
written healthcare declarations known as 
living wills will have legal status in minnesota beginning aug 1 
the state legislature this year passed a measure which allows 
adults to put in writing their preferences and instructions 
regarding care and treatment if they are terminally ill and not able 
to participate in treatment decisions 
about 40 states have statutes recognizing living will 
declarations 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
gov bob miller has proposed a hotline 
for reporting abuse of the states elderly but lawmakers branded it 
meaningless and are studying how to improve on the governors 
suggestion 
the proposal calls for a hotline operating monday through friday 
from 8 am to 5 pm senate finance committee chairman bill raggio 
directed members to study the cost of a 24hour hotline 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the 1989 legislature revamped the states 
guardianship laws provided more inhome services for the elderly 
and disabled and set up a system to investigate elder abuse neglect 
and exploitation 
nineteen measures directly affecting the elderly take effect in 
july including legal recognition of living wills the twoyear 
spending cycle that starts july 1 also puts 56 million into 
inhome services 
in revamping guardianships of the elderly lawmakers required 
courts to appoint an attorney to act essentially as an ombudsman for 
the individual and to make proceedings accessible and understandable 
to impaired people and required reports from guardians 
</TEXT>
