<TEXT>
france angered by britains rejection of a 
single european currency and central bank threatened monday to 
renege on an agreement that forms part of the drive for a united 
european market by 1992 
britains prime minister margaret thatcher refused at the opening 
session of a twoday summit to embrace a plan for a tight monetary 
union of the 12 nations of the european economic community 
her opposition prompted french president francois mitterrand to 
threaten to renege on promises for more liberalized money markets 
if there is no agreement as a totality then countries who 
are committed to lifting exchange controls could be led to revise 
their position a french spokesman quoted mitterrand as saying in 
the closeddoor session 
spanish officials worked late monday trying to win backing for a 
fourpoint compromise proposal to submit to the leaders tuesday the 
final day of the semiannual summit 
its most controversial point seeks backing for moves to create a 
common central bank 
the leaders had gone into the summit at odds over key parts of 
the plan supported most enthusiastically by france west germany 
and spain and opposed by britain 
this split surfaced in their daylong closeddoor talks 
the rough work was in the hands of president mitterrand who 
said it quite strongly while the nuances were with west german 
chancellor helmut kohl said dutch prime minister ruud lubbers 
kohl urged his colleagues to accept the farreaching changes 
mrs thatcher said she supported closer monetary and economic 
cooperation but objected to the two subsequent stages that would 
lead to a single central bank and a common currency in the trading 
bloc 
decisions on these matters are simply not on the current 
agenda a british official quoted mrs thatcher as telling other 
leaders during the closeddoor session we must stick to the 
practical and go for what needs to be done now 
britain was backed at times by the netherlands portugal and 
luxembourg 
the moves for monetary union have added a new dimension to the 
eecs plans to fashion a single market by the end of 1992 by that 
date the nations want to remove the many trade barriers that 
prevent the free movement of people goods services and money 
officials said there was general agreement the 12 nations should 
cooperate more in economic and monetary matters 
we commit ourselves to the goal of the economic and monetary 
union process said the british official what we have not 
committed ourselves to is a process as defined in the report 
as part of endorsing a first stage of the plan which would begin 
in july 1990 mrs thatcher pledged to link the pound to the other 
major european currencies by joining the exchange rate mechanism of 
the european monetary system 
