coffee futures prices sagged to an 11month low monday on new 
yorks coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange amid growing pessimism about 
the international coffee organizations ability to keep its grip on 
price controls 
on other markets orange juice futures soared corn and soybean 
futures dropped while wheat advanced livestock and meat futures 
rallied oil futures rose and precious metals slumped 
green unroasted coffee settled 163 cents to 605 cents lower 
with the contract for delivery in july at 111 a pound the 
markets lowest close since aug 2 1988 
the selloff was sparked by news friday that colombia the 
worlds secondlargest coffee producer would move to abolish all 
export quotas unless members of the international coffee 
organization approve a new pricesupport agreement at their meeting 
next monday in london 
the ico composed of 74 major coffeeproducing and consuming 
nations attempts to control coffee prices by limiting the amount of 
coffee that each producer country may sell to the consumers 
discord among the members has led to fears that the current 
6year agreement will expire sept 30 without a pact to succeed it 
leaving coffee prices open to freemarket forces for the first time 
since 1963 
ico members will consider two proposals next week one to extend 
the current agreement with no change in quotas and the other to 
extend the agreement with changes to increase the availability of 
mild arabica coffees the type most in demand 
the two proposals are expected to be voted on but both are 
expected to be rejected said sandra kaul a coffeemarket analyst 
in new york with shearson lehman hutton inc 
traders fear that if colombia introduces a motion to abandon all 
quotas other producer countries will approve it and coffee will 
flood the market 
