<TEXT>
ford motor co said monday that it will idle its 
chicago and atlanta assembly plants for a third week after their 
normal twoweek summer shutdown this year 
the week of july 17 will be added to both plants normal twoweek 
shutdown for changeover from production of 1989 to 1990model 
automobiles ford spokesman joel pitcoff said 
the extended shutdown resulted from a delay in obtaining parts 
for 1990 models with new passive restraint systems and wasnt meant 
to reduce inventories pitcoff said 
the chicago plant employs about 2300 hourly employees and the 
atlanta plant employs about 2150 both produce the popular ford 
taurus and mercury sable automobiles 
ford has about a 54day supply of taurus cars and a 59day supply 
of sable cars on hand compared with a normal 65day inventory at 
this time of year pitcoff said 
pitcoff was quoted by the new york times in tuesdays editions as 
saying that the parts delay caused the company to delay the start of 
1990 production by a week at each plant 
because of the delay ford asked its dealers to buy an extra 
weeks worth of 1989 models but the dealers balked because the 
company already had begun taking orders for the 1990 models the 
dealers reluctance prompted the company to shut the plants for an 
extra week 
</TEXT>
